KEVIN VLK: That's amazing.

00:01:45.780 --> 00:01:47.770
So you grew up in Mission
Hills, just outside of LA.

00:01:47.770 --> 00:01:48.080
Right?

00:01:48.080 --> 00:01:48.780
GEORGE LOPEZ: Yes.

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:50.080
KEVIN VLK: Raised
by your grandmother.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:52.000
And I read that you
wanted to comedy since you

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:52.880
were about 11 years old.

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:53.870
So what sparked that for you?

00:01:53.870 --> 00:01:55.100
Did you grow up in
a comedic household?

00:01:55.100 --> 00:01:56.308
Or where you just a goofball?

00:02:00.665 --> 00:02:04.320
GEORGE LOPEZ: You know what,
there was humor in the, house

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:07.610
but from a negative point.

00:02:07.610 --> 00:02:12.450
You know, I think sometimes the
negative is-- like, you know,

00:02:12.450 --> 00:02:16.540
in the tour right now,
if you see a kid now,

00:02:16.540 --> 00:02:20.150
you have to congratulate him
on everything that they do.

00:02:20.150 --> 00:02:21.100
Like waking up.

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:25.230
Hey, hi, Ryan.

00:02:25.230 --> 00:02:27.700
You woke up.

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:28.400
Hi.

00:02:28.400 --> 00:02:30.014
I was at Coffee
Bean-- this is true,

00:02:30.014 --> 00:02:31.430
this is where the
thing came from.

00:02:31.430 --> 00:02:35.330
So I was at Coffee Bean,
and the father says,

00:02:35.330 --> 00:02:39.480
can you go get me
some Sugar In The Raw?

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:43.660
And the kid walks across
Coffee Bean, and the dad's

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:45.660
complimenting,
you're walking great.

00:02:45.660 --> 00:02:47.130
You're walking great.

00:02:47.130 --> 00:02:48.210
You're walking great.

00:02:48.210 --> 00:02:50.020
I'm like, what the?

00:02:50.020 --> 00:02:54.310
So then, with me and my,
you know, negative positive.

00:02:54.310 --> 00:02:59.160
The joke I say is, our
parents only congratulated us

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:01.210
when we did something bad.

00:03:01.210 --> 00:03:04.330
Like if you crashed the
car, your whole family

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:08.330
was out front going, beautiful.

00:03:08.330 --> 00:03:09.410
Congratulations.

00:03:09.410 --> 00:03:12.090
Look what you did.

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:14.050
I don't know how you did
it, but you scratched

00:03:14.050 --> 00:03:16.740
both sides of the car.

00:03:16.740 --> 00:03:18.984
And I'm so proud.

00:03:18.984 --> 00:03:20.150
I'm prouder that I cosigned.

00:03:23.380 --> 00:03:25.710
But you know, it's
an easy-- you know,

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:30.014
like the formula for the comedy
came from the tough place

00:03:30.014 --> 00:03:30.680
where I grew up.

00:03:30.680 --> 00:03:34.100
But also because
everything was-- sometimes

00:03:34.100 --> 00:03:36.710
when things are kind of
like, not going well,

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:38.425
it's the funniest.

00:03:38.425 --> 00:03:41.572
You know, my grandmother,
who I miss, like every day.

00:03:41.572 --> 00:03:43.530
And I never thought I
would miss her that much.

00:03:43.530 --> 00:03:46.921
She told me, when I'm
gone, you're gonna miss me.

00:03:46.921 --> 00:03:47.670
But you know what?

00:03:47.670 --> 00:03:49.370
She was right.

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:52.089
So the one time, you
know, she had cancer,

00:03:52.089 --> 00:03:53.880
so I was taking her to
radiation, you know.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:04:01.240
And we get to the place,
and I said, OK Grandma, you

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:01.990
gotta go in there.

00:04:01.990 --> 00:04:03.270
She goes, I don't
wanna go in there.

00:04:03.270 --> 00:04:04.978
I said, Grandma, you
have to go in there.

00:04:04.978 --> 00:04:06.520
The doctor's waiting for you.

00:04:06.520 --> 00:04:08.700
And she goes, I'm
not going to go in.

00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:11.620
I said, Grandma, you
have to go get radiation.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:13.625
And she said, maybe I
don't want to be radiated.

00:04:16.365 --> 00:04:17.740
So I thought all that was funny.

00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:20.779
Me and her used to
have a great time.

00:04:20.779 --> 00:04:24.140
So you know, not until, I
think, when my show started,

00:04:24.140 --> 00:04:28.120
that "Time" magazine, they
wrote an article about me.

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:30.125
And then the guy in
the article said,

00:04:30.125 --> 00:04:31.500
I think George
Lopez should thank

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:34.210
his grandmother for
his success, because it

00:04:34.210 --> 00:04:36.540
seems to all come from her.

00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:37.920
And it's true.

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:39.717
It's true, everything
came from her.

00:04:39.717 --> 00:04:40.800
KEVIN VLK: That's amazing.

00:04:40.800 --> 00:04:43.650
So I kind of want to talk about
getting your rise into comedy.

00:04:43.650 --> 00:04:45.400
Because stand-up comedy
was huge in, like,

00:04:45.400 --> 00:04:48.360
the '70s and the '80s, with
like, Pryor, Cosby, Seinfeld.

00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:50.257
And then, kind of in
the late '80s and '90s

00:04:50.257 --> 00:04:51.590
it started to kind of just sink.

00:04:51.590 --> 00:04:53.730
And in the '90s, mid
'90s, it really hit low.

00:04:53.730 --> 00:04:55.250
But that's kind of when
you were going through it.

00:04:55.250 --> 00:04:57.160
So what kind of kept
you through, and kind of

00:04:57.160 --> 00:04:59.870
finding your voice, and saying
that I could actually do this?

00:05:02.569 --> 00:05:04.860
GEORGE LOPEZ: First of all,
I was afraid of everything,

00:05:04.860 --> 00:05:06.190
growing up.

00:05:06.190 --> 00:05:06.780
Afraid.

00:05:06.780 --> 00:05:11.770
So I would quit if
it got scary to me.

00:05:11.770 --> 00:05:16.220
Or if it got tough,
I would stop.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:20.180
And when I was playing
baseball-- I loved baseball,

00:05:20.180 --> 00:05:23.240
I still do-- but
when I was playing,

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:28.115
I got kicked off the team
for not being as disciplined

00:05:28.115 --> 00:05:29.860
as somebody else.

00:05:29.860 --> 00:05:33.230
And then the coach said to
me, you know your problem?

00:05:33.230 --> 00:05:35.220
When it gets tough, you quit.

00:05:35.220 --> 00:05:39.060
And it wasn't until, like
three years out of high school,

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:40.755
that I realized
that he was right.

00:05:40.755 --> 00:05:42.610
Like, he had nailed it.

00:05:42.610 --> 00:05:45.300
So I went back to
the school one day,

00:05:45.300 --> 00:05:48.320
and I waited 'till
after baseball practice,

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:50.920
and I walked up to him, and
I apologized for the way

00:05:50.920 --> 00:05:52.220
that I had treated him.

00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:56.600
And that he had taught me an
incredible lesson, of when

00:05:56.600 --> 00:05:59.220
things get tough,
things get better.

00:05:59.220 --> 00:06:04.960
And that everything
that I wanted to quit,

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:06.190
I didn't after that.

00:06:06.190 --> 00:06:07.480
And everything changed.

00:06:07.480 --> 00:06:12.377
And then I met Arsenio
Hall in February of 1989,

00:06:12.377 --> 00:06:13.460
his show had just started.

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:15.418
And that was a night that
I wasn't going to go.

00:06:15.418 --> 00:06:18.770
It was a Wednesday, and I
said, nah, I'm not going to go.

00:06:18.770 --> 00:06:21.199
And then I end up
convincing myself to go,

00:06:21.199 --> 00:06:21.990
and then I met him.

00:06:21.990 --> 00:06:26.762
And it really did change
the direction of my life.

00:06:26.762 --> 00:06:28.470
Because not only did
I get an opportunity

00:06:28.470 --> 00:06:30.570
to be on TV, on an
incredible show,

00:06:30.570 --> 00:06:35.390
but I also made a friend
that, we're still very close.

00:06:35.390 --> 00:06:38.130
We just went to a basketball
game, and we talk all the time.

00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:40.979
And I met somebody that
kind of understands

00:06:40.979 --> 00:06:42.020
what I was going through.

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:45.870
And it's a valuable friendship.

00:06:45.870 --> 00:06:48.070
KEVIN VLK: So your
first time onstage,

00:06:48.070 --> 00:06:50.520
was it good, or did you bomb?

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:52.300
GEORGE LOPEZ: Man.

00:06:52.300 --> 00:06:59.184
So the first time I go
onstage, I'm scared to death.

00:06:59.184 --> 00:07:00.600
And I had my friend
Ernie with me.

00:07:00.600 --> 00:07:02.266
You know I did the
show, that guy Ernie,

00:07:02.266 --> 00:07:03.500
there was a real Ernie.

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:07.900
And we went to-- it
was in Westwood--

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:12.600
and we bought-- I was 18,
I was still in high school.

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:19.420
And we paid a wino to go
into the liquor store,

00:07:19.420 --> 00:07:23.080
and buy us a bottle of wine.

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:25.610
And then he gave us a little
bottle, and we're like,

00:07:25.610 --> 00:07:27.000
don't they have bigger bottles?

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:28.950
He bought himself
a bigger bottle,

00:07:28.950 --> 00:07:32.060
and gave us the little one.

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:34.060
We didn't give him
money to buy his wine,

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:36.670
but he used our money to buy it.

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:40.554
So I took a little
bit of a drink

00:07:40.554 --> 00:07:41.720
to kind of sooth the nerves.

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:42.550
Didn't work.

00:07:42.550 --> 00:07:44.260
But it is frightening.

00:07:44.260 --> 00:07:49.480
You know, anything new, any job,
any place you move, any school,

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:52.990
education, people that you
meet, it's all-- initially,

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:54.477
your initial reaction is fear.

00:07:54.477 --> 00:07:56.060
You know, you're a
little bit nervous,

00:07:56.060 --> 00:07:57.185
you're a little bit afraid.

00:07:57.185 --> 00:08:00.460
But then when you get past
that, and convince yourself

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:02.762
that you're in the
right place, you really

00:08:02.762 --> 00:08:03.720
are in the right place.

00:08:03.720 --> 00:08:05.440
KEVIN VLK: So what got
you back up on the stage?

00:08:05.440 --> 00:08:07.356
If the first time was
scary and nerve-racking,

00:08:07.356 --> 00:08:09.876
and stuff, or was it
just, hey, I can't quit?

00:08:09.876 --> 00:08:14.770
GEORGE LOPEZ: You
know, I always felt

00:08:14.770 --> 00:08:17.370
like I was little bit
different than everybody

00:08:17.370 --> 00:08:18.680
that I had grown up around.

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:20.530
And even people in my family.

00:08:20.530 --> 00:08:22.150
That I just felt a
little different.

00:08:22.150 --> 00:08:26.490
It wasn't through
intelligence, no.

00:08:26.490 --> 00:08:28.979
But I just felt a little
different in the way

00:08:28.979 --> 00:08:30.020
that I thought, you know.

00:08:30.020 --> 00:08:33.839
And I started to write notes
when I was 11 years old.

00:08:33.839 --> 00:08:36.440
I still have some notebooks
from when I was 11.

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:41.589
And, yeah, I always thought
that I could be different.

00:08:41.589 --> 00:08:42.505
Like I felt different.

00:08:42.505 --> 00:08:45.210
Even when things
weren't going good,

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:48.130
I always felt that
I was different.

00:08:48.130 --> 00:08:50.210
KEVIN VLK: So did
you have a mentor?

00:08:50.210 --> 00:08:52.747
Kind of going through the
comedy circuit, someone who kind

00:08:52.747 --> 00:08:53.955
of took you under their wing?

00:08:56.760 --> 00:09:02.680
GEORGE LOPEZ: Well, you
know, I don't think I did.

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:05.270
You know, of the things that
I think I'm proudest of,

00:09:05.270 --> 00:09:10.410
is that Freddie Prinze, Sr.,
from "Chico and the Man,"

00:09:10.410 --> 00:09:12.920
was really the first person
that I saw that I said,

00:09:12.920 --> 00:09:14.720
you know, I think
I could do this.

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:16.400
I think he had an album.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:19.825
And he was Puerto
Rican and Hungarian,

00:09:19.825 --> 00:09:23.475
and he was playing Mexican.

00:09:23.475 --> 00:09:26.560
And then I said, you know, I
think this is a possibility.

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:29.220
So I started to focus
on him, and then

00:09:29.220 --> 00:09:32.970
he committed suicide in 1977,
and I was in 10th grade.

00:09:32.970 --> 00:09:37.710
It affected me a lot, because
I had been in love with him.

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:40.740
And then the first real loss
that I ever felt in my life,

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:43.400
that somebody that
I'd admired was gone.

00:09:43.400 --> 00:09:45.040
And then Richard
Pryor, you know,

00:09:45.040 --> 00:09:46.640
was somebody that I watched.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:51.710
And my grandmother
was-- my grandmother

00:09:51.710 --> 00:09:56.260
was not a fan of the
African American culture.

00:09:56.260 --> 00:10:01.570
So I say the only black person
that my grandmother allowed

00:10:01.570 --> 00:10:05.770
into the house was Richard
Pryor, on a VHS tape.

00:10:05.770 --> 00:10:07.310
That was it.

00:10:07.310 --> 00:10:09.280
All my friends would
have to stay outside,

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:12.020
even though when she left to
work, I brought them inside.

00:10:12.020 --> 00:10:16.750
But she was very
backwards in her thinking.

00:10:16.750 --> 00:10:20.116
But then also, I think
I told this story.

00:10:20.116 --> 00:10:20.990
This is a true story.

00:10:20.990 --> 00:10:22.365
Like, when my
grandmother started

00:10:22.365 --> 00:10:27.440
to get dementia and a
little bit of Alzheimer's, I

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:30.822
didn't put her in a home.

00:10:30.822 --> 00:10:32.490
I kept her in the house.

00:10:32.490 --> 00:10:35.880
But then I needed
to hire nurses.

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:43.900
And I said, you know, I think
I'm gonna hire black nurses,

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:49.900
so that my grandmother
would learn a lesson in race

00:10:49.900 --> 00:10:51.766
before she goes.

00:10:51.766 --> 00:10:53.950
Right?

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:54.450
True story.

00:10:54.450 --> 00:10:58.350
So I called the place, and
I said, I need some nurses.

00:10:58.350 --> 00:11:00.810
And they said, what kind
of nurses do you need?

00:11:00.810 --> 00:11:03.830
And I said black.

00:11:03.830 --> 00:11:10.920
And then lady goes,
sir, we do not

00:11:10.920 --> 00:11:15.850
give out our nurses by
the color of their skin,

00:11:15.850 --> 00:11:17.640
but their qualifications.

00:11:17.640 --> 00:11:20.020
What kind of
qualifications do you need?

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:21.740
I said, no, they
have to be black.

00:11:21.740 --> 00:11:23.610
And she was like, who is this?

00:11:23.610 --> 00:11:25.557
And I said, it's George Lopez.

00:11:25.557 --> 00:11:26.890
And you know what the lady said?

00:11:26.890 --> 00:11:29.860
How black?

00:11:29.860 --> 00:11:32.340
There's the money.

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:33.200
I swear it, too.

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:34.440
How black?

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:36.910
And I said, now we're talking.

00:11:36.910 --> 00:11:42.797
And then I had
some-- and you know,

00:11:42.797 --> 00:11:44.380
the greatest thing
is, my grandmother,

00:11:44.380 --> 00:11:48.730
they would sit next to
each other, and watch TV,

00:11:48.730 --> 00:11:51.710
and say, this is my best friend.

00:11:51.710 --> 00:11:54.210
And then I would
be like, she never

00:11:54.210 --> 00:11:56.920
told me I was her best friend.

00:11:56.920 --> 00:11:58.580
But you know, it worked out.

00:11:58.580 --> 00:12:01.410
It worked out, yeah.

00:12:01.410 --> 00:12:07.205
And then, it was years,
and she wouldn't go.

00:12:07.205 --> 00:12:08.020
You know?

00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:17.400
So I told her one
time, you know,

00:12:17.400 --> 00:12:19.210
she had a hart thing
at the hospital.

00:12:19.210 --> 00:12:22.910
I said, Grandma,
you know, can go.

00:12:25.610 --> 00:12:26.445
She went like this.

00:12:30.059 --> 00:12:32.985
She said, I'm not
going anywhere.

00:12:32.985 --> 00:12:34.860
KEVIN VLK: So every
comedian kind of has, you

00:12:34.860 --> 00:12:37.290
know, two stories from
kind of like, their tours.

00:12:37.290 --> 00:12:38.430
It's kind of like their
biggest bomb, and also

00:12:38.430 --> 00:12:40.850
just their weirdest, funnies
story from being on tour.

00:12:40.850 --> 00:12:41.760
So do you have
one of those, kind

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:43.968
of when you were kind of
rising up through the ranks?

00:12:46.755 --> 00:12:48.950
The most memorable moment?

00:12:48.950 --> 00:12:51.290
GEORGE LOPEZ: I got a
gun pulled on me one time

00:12:51.290 --> 00:12:52.715
in an alley in Indianapolis.

00:12:52.715 --> 00:12:54.090
KEVIN VLK: That
took a dark turn.

00:12:54.090 --> 00:12:55.699
GEORGE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:12:55.699 --> 00:12:57.490
KEVIN VLK: Terrible
questions, interviewer.

00:12:57.490 --> 00:12:58.350
Stop it.

00:12:58.350 --> 00:13:00.590
GEORGE LOPEZ: I had a
guy pull a gun on me.

00:13:00.590 --> 00:13:02.990
He didn't like
what I was saying,

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:09.555
and he says, get on your knees.

00:13:12.180 --> 00:13:17.190
And I said, literally, I said,
I'm not getting on my knees.

00:13:17.190 --> 00:13:18.315
He goes, get on your knees.

00:13:18.315 --> 00:13:22.750
I said, I'm not gonna
get on my knees.

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:25.640
And then he said,
I remember he said,

00:13:25.640 --> 00:13:28.040
I'm not going to
shoot you, because I

00:13:28.040 --> 00:13:31.650
believe in apple pie and
America, or something

00:13:31.650 --> 00:13:32.150
like that.

00:13:32.150 --> 00:13:33.442
Was that in the Chevy slogan?

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:38.020
So he says, get out of here.

00:13:38.020 --> 00:13:39.570
Like, he says, get out of here.

00:13:39.570 --> 00:13:41.500
And he says, run.

00:13:41.500 --> 00:13:43.740
And I'm like, I'm not gonna run.

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:46.100
So I didn't get on my
knees, because I'm not

00:13:46.100 --> 00:13:47.220
going to do that, ever.

00:13:47.220 --> 00:13:50.960
And then I didn't run,
because, you know, I'm Chicano,

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:53.290
I don't run.

00:13:53.290 --> 00:13:57.900
And then, the minute I
turned the corner I took off.

00:13:57.900 --> 00:13:59.960
I ran out of my jacket.

00:13:59.960 --> 00:14:01.710
I was running, and
my jacket came off.

00:14:01.710 --> 00:14:03.740
I looked back, I
just kept running.

00:14:03.740 --> 00:14:06.280
I ran out of my jacket,
I was running so crazy,

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:09.240
my arms were flying,
my jacket came off.

00:14:09.240 --> 00:14:12.800
And then I didn't
go back to get it.

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:16.730
I never ran out of my jacket.

00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:18.020
But he didn't see me run.

00:14:18.020 --> 00:14:21.658
He came around looking
for me, but I was gone.

00:14:21.658 --> 00:14:24.267
KEVIN VLK: You know,
hearing your stand-up,

00:14:24.267 --> 00:14:25.600
it seems to be all new material.

00:14:25.600 --> 00:14:27.490
I know a lot of
comedians-- like Seinfeld,

00:14:27.490 --> 00:14:29.781
he mixes kind of like his
greatest hits with new stuff.

00:14:29.781 --> 00:14:31.830
And Louis C.K. kind of
starts fresh every time

00:14:31.830 --> 00:14:32.585
he kinds of goes on tour.

00:14:32.585 --> 00:14:34.390
So what's your process for
coming up with material?

00:14:34.390 --> 00:14:36.790
GEORGE LOPEZ: You know, I kind
of weave stuff in and out.

00:14:36.790 --> 00:14:41.910
You know, there's things that
are like synonymous with--

00:14:41.910 --> 00:14:46.055
and I don't even know if they're
really jokes, per se, you know.

00:14:46.055 --> 00:14:47.180
KEVIN VLK: They're stories.

00:14:47.180 --> 00:14:48.480
GEORGE LOPEZ: They're,
yeah, kind of recollections.

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:50.915
You know, like, there's
the Jack in the Box one.

00:14:54.020 --> 00:15:01.290
The Jack in the Box one
started because in Sacramento,

00:15:01.290 --> 00:15:03.710
after we did the punchline,
I went to Jack in the Box,

00:15:03.710 --> 00:15:05.610
and I rolled up
and the guy's like,

00:15:05.610 --> 00:15:07.446
welcome to Jack in the
Bok, can I hep you?

00:15:07.446 --> 00:15:08.837
And I was like, what?

00:15:08.837 --> 00:15:11.420
And the guy's like, welcome to
Jack in the Bok, can I hel you?

00:15:14.510 --> 00:15:16.770
I said, is this Jack in the Box?

00:15:16.770 --> 00:15:20.130
He's like, say, Jack in
the Bok, can I hel you?

00:15:20.130 --> 00:15:22.921
And I said, yeah, can I have--
just the way I laid it out

00:15:22.921 --> 00:15:23.420
in the joke.

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:24.420
Can I have a jumbo jack?

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:26.560
You want a yumbo yak?

00:15:26.560 --> 00:15:29.900
And he goes, frem fry?

00:15:29.900 --> 00:15:30.790
Frem fry?

00:15:30.790 --> 00:15:32.720
I said.

00:15:32.720 --> 00:15:36.920
And then he's like,
papas fritas, stupid!

00:15:36.920 --> 00:15:45.190
But he did say, he
said pexi, and esprite.

00:15:45.190 --> 00:15:46.240
He said esprite.

00:15:46.240 --> 00:15:48.570
Esprite.

00:15:48.570 --> 00:15:53.650
So then the next night
I did it, and boom.

00:15:53.650 --> 00:15:55.970
One time I was
outside of a club,

00:15:55.970 --> 00:15:57.652
and these Latinos
were there, you know,

00:15:57.652 --> 00:15:59.360
they were trying to
be, like, successful,

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:01.660
you know, they're sitting there.

00:16:01.660 --> 00:16:03.550
And you know, and I'm
sitting right there.

00:16:03.550 --> 00:16:05.894
So they're going,
remember that time?

00:16:05.894 --> 00:16:07.560
And they're going,
remember that time we

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:08.610
went over to that place?

00:16:08.610 --> 00:16:09.440
And they said, which place?

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:09.940
You member.

00:16:09.940 --> 00:16:10.900
Member the place?

00:16:10.900 --> 00:16:12.730
They go, member?

00:16:12.730 --> 00:16:13.270
You member.

00:16:13.270 --> 00:16:14.900
And they said, I don't member.

00:16:14.900 --> 00:16:17.090
Yeah, you don't member?

00:16:17.090 --> 00:16:18.390
And then it was all negative.

00:16:18.390 --> 00:16:20.650
Member your mom
fe-- oh, yeah, that.

00:16:20.650 --> 00:16:23.230
Yeah, it was all
around a negative.

00:16:23.230 --> 00:16:24.770
Member your mom fell that time?

00:16:24.770 --> 00:16:26.650
Oh, yeah, I member.

00:16:26.650 --> 00:16:28.440
And that I did
that one, and then

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:31.130
that one became huge, as well.

00:16:31.130 --> 00:16:35.566
So all of the-- I've got a pain
in my chest, I can't breathe.

00:16:35.566 --> 00:16:37.260
That was one.

00:16:37.260 --> 00:16:39.260
I know ha, was one.

00:16:39.260 --> 00:16:39.990
I know ha.

00:16:39.990 --> 00:16:42.142
And they say they
it all the time.

00:16:42.142 --> 00:16:43.100
I hear it all the time.

00:16:43.100 --> 00:16:45.940
So you know, I kind
of had-- you know,

00:16:45.940 --> 00:16:52.035
I thought our culture was
funny enough to kind of--

00:16:52.035 --> 00:16:55.080
and it's funny, because
it's not-- you know,

00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:56.860
people say, aw, it's
making fun of it.

00:16:56.860 --> 00:17:03.940
But you know, Bill Cosby,
or Seinfeld, or those guys,

00:17:03.940 --> 00:17:04.815
they all had a thing.

00:17:04.815 --> 00:17:06.564
And it's funny, Bill
Cosby, what you know?

00:17:06.564 --> 00:17:07.310
Hey, the thing--

00:17:12.769 --> 00:17:13.810
KEVIN VLK: Next question.

00:17:13.810 --> 00:17:16.148
So--

00:17:16.148 --> 00:17:17.579
GEORGE LOPEZ: I
say it almost like

00:17:17.579 --> 00:17:18.828
in "The Silence of the Lambs."

00:17:18.828 --> 00:17:22.230
It puts the lotion
in the basket.

00:17:22.230 --> 00:17:26.250
KEVIN VLK: So Sandra Bullock,
and her production company,

00:17:26.250 --> 00:17:27.861
they gave you your
big break on TV.

00:17:27.861 --> 00:17:28.610
One of her scouts.

00:17:28.610 --> 00:17:30.193
GEORGE LOPEZ: Sandra
Bullock did, yes.

00:17:30.193 --> 00:17:31.672
KEVIN VLK: And I
did not know that.

00:17:31.672 --> 00:17:32.910
That's really, really cool.

00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:35.490
So she kind of noticed
that there wasn't really

00:17:35.490 --> 00:17:39.144
a true, just Hispanic,
television show.

00:17:39.144 --> 00:17:40.560
GEORGE LOPEZ: She
lives in Austin,

00:17:40.560 --> 00:17:43.290
and she fell in love
with the culture.

00:17:43.290 --> 00:17:48.590
And she started to say,
how come there's not-- I

00:17:48.590 --> 00:17:50.970
think she had done
"Miss Congeniality,"

00:17:50.970 --> 00:17:53.240
and then I think her
mom was not well,

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:57.141
she had kind of become kind of
distant from acting, you know,

00:17:57.141 --> 00:17:58.890
because she was taking
care of her family.

00:17:58.890 --> 00:18:06.510
So then she actually had a show
idea that was about teenagers,

00:18:06.510 --> 00:18:07.620
like Latino teenagers.

00:18:07.620 --> 00:18:10.390
And they wanted me to be the
father of these teenagers.

00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:14.100
But the father, he wasn't
in the lead of the show,

00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:15.530
the kids were.

00:18:15.530 --> 00:18:19.150
So then I got her to come
and see me do stand up.

00:18:19.150 --> 00:18:23.890
And after, she came back in,
and she goes, forget my idea.

00:18:23.890 --> 00:18:28.550
I want to do what's in your
act, because that's the better

00:18:28.550 --> 00:18:29.500
story.

00:18:29.500 --> 00:18:31.300
And then I did the grandmother.

00:18:31.300 --> 00:18:32.740
My Grandma's name was Bennie.

00:18:32.740 --> 00:18:34.930
They lady on the show
was named Bennie.

00:18:34.930 --> 00:18:36.940
My best friend was named Ernie.

00:18:36.940 --> 00:18:39.335
The guy was named Ernie.

00:18:39.335 --> 00:18:42.010
I was married, my wife was
named Ann, it was Angie.

00:18:42.010 --> 00:18:45.190
Max was my grandmother's
dog's name.

00:18:45.190 --> 00:18:46.580
I named him Max.

00:18:46.580 --> 00:18:49.630
And Carmen was Cheech's
daughter's name.

00:18:49.630 --> 00:18:51.720
I thought that that would
be a good one, Carmen.

00:18:51.720 --> 00:18:56.920
And then the Powers
Aviation, I worked

00:18:56.920 --> 00:19:00.310
at a place called Powers.

00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:02.650
I shipped books, like back end.

00:19:02.650 --> 00:19:06.785
You know, how to play
blackjack, how to read minds,

00:19:06.785 --> 00:19:09.840
you know, those how to books,
like how to grow a garden.

00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:10.840
I shipped books.

00:19:10.840 --> 00:19:12.280
Like, I shipped.

00:19:12.280 --> 00:19:14.964
Like I got the thing,
I put the box in there.

00:19:14.964 --> 00:19:19.920
And the guy's name
was Melvin Powers.

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:22.160
And I remember one day, he
came and he had some guys,

00:19:22.160 --> 00:19:24.910
he was taking a tour,
and he goes, hey, George,

00:19:24.910 --> 00:19:25.690
how's everything?

00:19:25.690 --> 00:19:27.460
And I said, great, Melvin.

00:19:27.460 --> 00:19:30.864
And then he looked at me like,
did you just call me Melvin?

00:19:30.864 --> 00:19:32.530
And I got fired that
day for calling him

00:19:32.530 --> 00:19:35.760
Melvin, instead of Mr.
Powers, in front of guests.

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:38.960
So when I did my
TV show, I named

00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:42.590
one of the guys Melvin Powers.

00:19:42.590 --> 00:19:44.920
One of the brothers
that owned the place.

00:19:44.920 --> 00:19:51.350
So I used all kind of real
life names and situations.

00:19:51.350 --> 00:19:53.340
KEVIN VLK: And it
ran for six seasons,

00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:57.150
and was successful on ABC,
but then it got canceled,

00:19:57.150 --> 00:19:58.647
and then it found
a whole new life,

00:19:58.647 --> 00:20:00.480
and was even more
successful in syndication.

00:20:00.480 --> 00:20:02.396
So do you just think it
was ahead of its time,

00:20:02.396 --> 00:20:06.064
or what attributes it to the
success that it had afterwards?

00:20:06.064 --> 00:20:08.230
GEORGE LOPEZ: Well, you
know I think that, you know,

00:20:08.230 --> 00:20:09.640
ABC moved it around
a little bit,

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:13.720
and then it struggled to
find, like, a main spot.

00:20:13.720 --> 00:20:15.137
But people liked
it when I was on,

00:20:15.137 --> 00:20:16.428
although it wasn't a big thing.

00:20:16.428 --> 00:20:17.860
But I thought the
fact that people

00:20:17.860 --> 00:20:21.180
could see it at the same time,
and see back to back episodes,

00:20:21.180 --> 00:20:24.440
because we had 120 of
them, that it became--

00:20:24.440 --> 00:20:31.440
and it hasn't been off
the air since 2002.

00:20:31.440 --> 00:20:34.830
Professionally, I think it's
the thing I'm proudest of.

00:20:34.830 --> 00:20:37.950
Because I took some
painful things in my life,

00:20:37.950 --> 00:20:40.490
and I put them in that show.

00:20:40.490 --> 00:20:46.480
And when I was younger
man, I'd gotten arrested,

00:20:46.480 --> 00:20:49.400
and I was in jail in Van Nuys.

00:20:49.400 --> 00:20:51.630
And I'm sitting
kind of like this.

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:54.190
And then somebody
sits next to me,

00:20:54.190 --> 00:20:58.050
and they're wearing
toenail polish.

00:20:58.050 --> 00:21:01.120
And I look down,
and I look up, it's

00:21:01.120 --> 00:21:03.970
a guy in an orange jumpsuit,
with toenail polish,

00:21:03.970 --> 00:21:05.730
and blond hair.

00:21:05.730 --> 00:21:08.650
Big guy, sitting next to me.

00:21:08.650 --> 00:21:12.180
So the guard comes to the
door, and he goes, Lopez?

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:15.480
And I stand up, and
the dude stands up.

00:21:15.480 --> 00:21:18.090
And the guard goes,
no, Mrs. Lopez.

00:21:18.090 --> 00:21:18.900
This is great.

00:21:21.642 --> 00:21:24.180
And you know what, I
put that in the show.

00:21:24.180 --> 00:21:26.560
That whole scene, where I was
in jail, and the guy came,

00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:29.710
and thing, I put the whole
thing in there, word for word.

00:21:29.710 --> 00:21:30.820
Word for word.

00:21:30.820 --> 00:21:32.010
No, Mrs. Lopez.

00:21:32.010 --> 00:21:32.510
Great.

00:21:35.606 --> 00:21:37.230
KEVIN VLK: What I
was really shocked by

00:21:37.230 --> 00:21:38.420
was that you were one
of only, actually,

00:21:38.420 --> 00:21:40.340
four Hispanics to ever
really lead a sitcom.

00:21:40.340 --> 00:21:42.715
It was Desi in "I Love Lucy,"
Freddie, who you mentioned,

00:21:42.715 --> 00:21:44.900
in "Chico and the Man,"
Paul Rodriguez in "Pablo."

00:21:44.900 --> 00:21:48.474
But these were TV shows
really aired decades apart.

00:21:48.474 --> 00:21:50.140
"Lucy" in the '50s,
"Chico" in the '70s,

00:21:50.140 --> 00:21:52.780
"Pablo" in the '80s, and
then almost 20 years gap

00:21:52.780 --> 00:21:54.190
until your show in 2002.

00:21:54.190 --> 00:21:57.350
So why the long
gaps, do you think?

00:21:57.350 --> 00:22:01.130
GEORGE LOPEZ: Well, no
disrespect to Paul Rodriguez,

00:22:01.130 --> 00:22:02.740
but a.k.a.

00:22:02.740 --> 00:22:07.980
Pablo only was on three
weeks, and I was on 120.

00:22:07.980 --> 00:22:14.900
So Desi Arnaz was
Cuban, and it was

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:20.320
called "I Love Lucy." "Chico
and the Man" was Freddie Prinze,

00:22:20.320 --> 00:22:22.320
and Chico was his name.

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:25.502
George Lopez.

00:22:25.502 --> 00:22:27.600
KEVIN VLK: So you're the first.

00:22:27.600 --> 00:22:30.200
GEORGE LOPEZ: The
only Mexican, so far.

00:22:30.200 --> 00:22:31.076
So that's impressive.

00:22:31.076 --> 00:22:32.504
[APPLAUSE]

00:22:35.314 --> 00:22:36.730
KEVIN VLK: Were
there any TV shows

00:22:36.730 --> 00:22:38.110
that you watched
when you grew up

00:22:38.110 --> 00:22:40.400
that influenced you
to create your show,

00:22:40.400 --> 00:22:42.608
or was it all just kind of
pulled from your stand-up?

00:22:42.608 --> 00:22:45.460
GEORGE LOPEZ: No, I think, like,
you know, "Taxi," or "Barney

00:22:45.460 --> 00:22:51.330
Miller," or, you know,
"Rosanne," and stuff like that

00:22:51.330 --> 00:22:53.510
was really influential.

00:22:53.510 --> 00:22:56.580
Seinfeld, and, you know.

00:22:56.580 --> 00:22:59.480
It's interesting, you
never know what you put out

00:22:59.480 --> 00:23:03.490
to the universe, like you never
really think about-- you know,

00:23:03.490 --> 00:23:06.969
people can make themselves
sick by worrying,

00:23:06.969 --> 00:23:08.510
and people can make
themselves better

00:23:08.510 --> 00:23:10.790
by being happy, and
being cheerful, and being

00:23:10.790 --> 00:23:13.050
positive, and being kind.

00:23:13.050 --> 00:23:19.110
And just, you know, putting
out positive energy.

00:23:19.110 --> 00:23:24.370
I used to watch Drew Carey, and
Bruce Helford and Drew Carey

00:23:24.370 --> 00:23:25.280
created the show.

00:23:25.280 --> 00:23:28.110
And I would say to the
TV, I would be like--

00:23:28.110 --> 00:23:30.590
because I knew Drew
Carey-- I would say, man,

00:23:30.590 --> 00:23:32.630
where's my Bruce Helford at?

00:23:32.630 --> 00:23:35.230
Where's my Bruce Helford?

00:23:35.230 --> 00:23:39.647
So when I did George Lopez,
I did it with Bruce Helford.

00:23:39.647 --> 00:23:40.230
Is that crazy?

00:23:40.230 --> 00:23:40.670
KEVIN VLK: Wow.

00:23:40.670 --> 00:23:41.461
GEORGE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:23:41.461 --> 00:23:44.800
And then I told my wife the
story about Bruce Helford,

00:23:44.800 --> 00:23:46.440
the one time we were
doing interviews,

00:23:46.440 --> 00:23:48.250
and I was in the
hallway, and he was

00:23:48.250 --> 00:23:50.390
on the TV in the hallway
talking about me.

00:23:50.390 --> 00:23:52.566
And started crying,
because I was like,

00:23:52.566 --> 00:23:54.802
you know, there he is.

00:23:54.802 --> 00:23:56.530
KEVIN VLK: Wow.

00:23:56.530 --> 00:23:58.220
How are you able to--
because you appeal

00:23:58.220 --> 00:23:59.934
to such a diverse audience.

00:23:59.934 --> 00:24:01.600
Is that a conscious
decision, or are you

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:04.060
just kind of, what's
funny is funny?

00:24:04.060 --> 00:24:08.300
GEORGE LOPEZ: Well, listen, I
mean, if you look like this.

00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:12.810
I mean, anybody could look like
Mario Lopez and be successful.

00:24:12.810 --> 00:24:14.355
You know, try looking like this.

00:24:16.870 --> 00:24:19.620
You've gotta be funny to be
successful and look like this.

00:24:19.620 --> 00:24:22.209
So I just thought
that-- you know,

00:24:22.209 --> 00:24:23.750
at first people
thought it was really

00:24:23.750 --> 00:24:26.550
kind of Latino based humor,
and then if you look at it now,

00:24:26.550 --> 00:24:32.060
it's very social and economic
levels of things that we did.

00:24:32.060 --> 00:24:37.340
And you look at things that
Latinos do, just in general,

00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:41.871
like you have a dining room
table with every chair's

00:24:41.871 --> 00:24:42.370
different.

00:24:45.364 --> 00:24:47.860
You know.

00:24:47.860 --> 00:24:51.310
All the pots and
pans are in the oven.

00:24:51.310 --> 00:24:52.230
You know.

00:24:52.230 --> 00:24:53.106
You know what I mean?

00:24:53.106 --> 00:24:54.438
You're like, where are the pots?

00:24:54.438 --> 00:24:55.560
They're in the oven.

00:24:55.560 --> 00:24:56.970
Everything's in the oven.

00:25:00.540 --> 00:25:04.091
Oh my god, I mean, there's
so many things that my--

00:25:04.091 --> 00:25:06.007
KEVIN VLK: If you guys
want to start lining up

00:25:06.007 --> 00:25:07.316
for questions, too,
we're going to start

00:25:07.316 --> 00:25:07.590
answering your questions.

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:09.423
GEORGE LOPEZ: Also, my
grandmother never put

00:25:09.423 --> 00:25:12.200
anything in a Ziploc bag.

00:25:12.200 --> 00:25:18.140
So you would eat ice cream,
and it tasted like tamales,

00:25:18.140 --> 00:25:21.540
because the tamales that
were in there from Christmas,

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:23.680
the fragrance had gotten
into the ice cream.

00:25:23.680 --> 00:25:25.793
And then you're eating ice
cream, and you're like,

00:25:25.793 --> 00:25:29.660
this tastes like tamales.

00:25:29.660 --> 00:25:31.920
And then the whole
thing, I really

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:33.680
did make snow
cones from scraping

00:25:33.680 --> 00:25:37.730
the ice from the
freezer, and putting 7UP.

00:25:40.917 --> 00:25:43.375
You know, what's crazy now too,
is kids are like engineers.

00:25:43.375 --> 00:25:44.750
You know what we did?

00:25:44.750 --> 00:25:47.370
As an engineer, we'd
try to fill the ice tray

00:25:47.370 --> 00:25:50.060
to make ice without spilling
it before you got it

00:25:50.060 --> 00:25:51.710
to the refrigerator.

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:53.220
That was our engineering.

00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:56.540
Making Kool-Aid with cellophane
on top, with toothpicks

00:25:56.540 --> 00:25:59.850
so that you've got a little,
like a toothpick ice cube,

00:25:59.850 --> 00:26:01.940
that tasted like
chorizo from the thing.

00:26:05.130 --> 00:26:05.830
Or foil.

00:26:05.830 --> 00:26:08.010
Like, I would bring a
plate back with foil,

00:26:08.010 --> 00:26:10.510
and then the guy would be going,
my mom wants her foil back.

00:26:10.510 --> 00:26:11.593
And it was over the plate.

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:16.100
Yeah, they fold it
and put in there.

00:26:16.100 --> 00:26:18.560
KEVIN VLK: Oh my
god, that's so funny.

00:26:18.560 --> 00:26:20.450
And then, so you
went from your sitcom

00:26:20.450 --> 00:26:21.989
over to "Lopez Tonight," on TBS.

00:26:21.989 --> 00:26:22.780
GEORGE LOPEZ: Yeah.

00:26:22.780 --> 00:26:25.382
KEVIN VLK: And so, what was
the biggest difference for you,

00:26:25.382 --> 00:26:27.340
going from-- obviously,
other than the format--

00:26:27.340 --> 00:26:30.249
but going from a sitcom with
multiple cameras, to a--

00:26:30.249 --> 00:26:31.790
GEORGE LOPEZ: You
know what the thing

00:26:31.790 --> 00:26:35.502
is, you never want to work in
a place where you're stifled.

00:26:35.502 --> 00:26:37.210
Like every day, you
go, and they tell you

00:26:37.210 --> 00:26:38.168
you can't do something.

00:26:38.168 --> 00:26:40.920
The talk show, it lasted two
years, but every day was,

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:43.450
you don't, you can't do
this, you can't do that.

00:26:43.450 --> 00:26:45.060
Too many Latinos are watching.

00:26:45.060 --> 00:26:46.480
Not enough women are watching.

00:26:46.480 --> 00:26:47.860
Too many women are watching.

00:26:47.860 --> 00:26:49.810
Too many Latinos are watching.

00:26:49.810 --> 00:26:52.329
Too many black
people are watching.

00:26:52.329 --> 00:26:53.870
Not enough black
people are watching.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:55.490
And every day, it was that.

00:26:55.490 --> 00:26:59.480
So even the last two
years, was amazing,

00:26:59.480 --> 00:27:01.230
because, you know,
they say they want you,

00:27:01.230 --> 00:27:04.480
and then they bring you in, and
then they make you different.

00:27:04.480 --> 00:27:06.054
And I didn't want
to be different.

00:27:06.054 --> 00:27:07.470
That's what I love
about stand-up,

00:27:07.470 --> 00:27:11.330
is that nobody can say what
you can say or not say.

00:27:11.330 --> 00:27:13.795
You know, they either
laugh, or they don't laugh.

00:27:13.795 --> 00:27:16.870
I'll take that risk.

00:27:16.870 --> 00:27:18.620
KEVIN VLK: And what
was the biggest lesson

00:27:18.620 --> 00:27:22.060
you learned just from doing a
sitcom and doing a talk show?

00:27:22.060 --> 00:27:24.220
GEORGE LOPEZ: You
know what, you learn

00:27:24.220 --> 00:27:25.860
to be dedicated to
your work, and to be

00:27:25.860 --> 00:27:27.120
prepared all the time.

00:27:27.120 --> 00:27:29.680
That this business
is tough enough

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:32.910
for anybody of any color,
but the lack of preparation,

00:27:32.910 --> 00:27:37.730
or when you're not sufficiently
educated or prepared,

00:27:37.730 --> 00:27:39.490
can hurt you.

00:27:39.490 --> 00:27:41.950
And then you think it's
because of you or what you are,

00:27:41.950 --> 00:27:44.140
but really it's just that
you're just not prepared.

00:27:44.140 --> 00:27:48.360
So it taught me to work
while people were sleeping,

00:27:48.360 --> 00:27:52.610
and to write while
people were resting.

00:27:52.610 --> 00:27:58.900
And I dedicated to my work
to myself, and it worked out.

00:27:58.900 --> 00:28:00.210
KEVIN VLK: Yeah.

00:28:00.210 --> 00:28:02.459
And then you transitioned
to-- well, not transitioned,

00:28:02.459 --> 00:28:03.950
but you've done a
lot movies, too.

00:28:03.950 --> 00:28:06.430
With critical success,
with "Real Women Have

00:28:06.430 --> 00:28:09.239
Curves," "Bread and Roses,"
and now, "Spare Parts,"

00:28:09.239 --> 00:28:10.530
which just came out in January.

00:28:10.530 --> 00:28:12.700
And that's based on
a true story of four

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:14.700
undocumented Mexican
American teenagers

00:28:14.700 --> 00:28:18.640
from Phoenix, who team up for
an underwater robot competition,

00:28:18.640 --> 00:28:20.800
national robotics competition.

00:28:20.800 --> 00:28:22.690
Marisa Tomei is in it.

00:28:22.690 --> 00:28:24.640
So I've seen a lot of
comedians, you included,

00:28:24.640 --> 00:28:26.139
do some of their
best work in drama.

00:28:26.139 --> 00:28:29.240
You are a very, very good
dramatic actor in your movies.

00:28:29.240 --> 00:28:31.520
Patton Oswalt did it in
"Young Adult" and "Big Fan."

00:28:31.520 --> 00:28:33.240
And Jim Carrey,
"Eternal Sunshine."

00:28:33.240 --> 00:28:35.885
Robin Williams in "Good Will
Hunting" and "What Dreams

00:28:35.885 --> 00:28:36.402
may Come."

00:28:36.402 --> 00:28:38.610
So what do you think it is
about comedians just being

00:28:38.610 --> 00:28:39.570
really good dramatic actors?

00:28:39.570 --> 00:28:40.695
Because you're really good.

00:28:43.480 --> 00:28:45.730
GEORGE LOPEZ: I think that
there's kind of a built in,

00:28:45.730 --> 00:28:47.550
when you take a couple
of hits, and you

00:28:47.550 --> 00:28:49.495
know what it's
like to have pain,

00:28:49.495 --> 00:28:55.000
and you tap into what is
natural, in kind of our lives.

00:28:55.000 --> 00:28:58.870
That things, of
people that have left,

00:28:58.870 --> 00:29:02.540
or things that you felt,
that you kind of carry.

00:29:02.540 --> 00:29:07.050
And it does help you become
a more dramatic actor.

00:29:07.050 --> 00:29:08.890
But, you know, in that
movie, "Spare Parts,"

00:29:08.890 --> 00:29:12.860
which is a very important move
because of these kids doing

00:29:12.860 --> 00:29:16.730
something, pretty
much impossible, that

00:29:16.730 --> 00:29:18.840
for Latino kids
from Arizona could

00:29:18.840 --> 00:29:21.540
create a robot for under $800.

00:29:21.540 --> 00:29:24.700
Wire it, and do the
coding all themselves.

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:27.350
And beat MIT.

00:29:27.350 --> 00:29:31.870
And beat Stanford, and
Harvard, and Cornell.

00:29:31.870 --> 00:29:33.410
And they beat everybody.

00:29:33.410 --> 00:29:34.840
And they only
entered-- you know,

00:29:34.840 --> 00:29:37.260
this is a very Latino
thing-- they entered

00:29:37.260 --> 00:29:40.820
not to lose to high schools, but
never thinking about winning.

00:29:40.820 --> 00:29:42.700
So they didn't
say, we just don't

00:29:42.700 --> 00:29:44.910
want to lose to high
schools, they never thought,

00:29:44.910 --> 00:29:45.590
we could win.

00:29:45.590 --> 00:29:47.560
So we have to change
that thinking, too,

00:29:47.560 --> 00:29:49.050
that you can win.

00:29:49.050 --> 00:29:51.120
And you can beat, if you
think you're the best,

00:29:51.120 --> 00:29:53.280
you could beat
anybody who thinks

00:29:53.280 --> 00:29:55.270
they're as good as you
are, if not better.

00:29:55.270 --> 00:29:55.952
KEVIN VLK: Wow.

00:29:55.952 --> 00:29:57.743
All right, we'll take
an audience question.

00:29:57.743 --> 00:29:58.870
GEORGE LOPEZ: Yes.

00:29:58.870 --> 00:30:01.370
AUDIENCE: First of all, thanks
for coming to Google, George.

00:30:01.370 --> 00:30:04.078
GEORGE LOPEZ: No, hey,
listen, thank you, Google.

00:30:04.078 --> 00:30:05.572
[APPLAUSE]

00:30:08.270 --> 00:30:10.150
I'm deeply touched.

00:30:10.150 --> 00:30:12.472
You know, Ming, my friend,
has been very kind to me.

00:30:12.472 --> 00:30:13.680
He's my brother, right there.

00:30:13.680 --> 00:30:15.480
So, Ming.

00:30:15.480 --> 00:30:20.740
I met Ming at MIT,
with the Dalai Lama.

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:23.730
Ming is, how long have
you known His Holiness?

00:30:23.730 --> 00:30:25.050
MING: I don't know, many years.

00:30:25.050 --> 00:30:26.110
GEORGE LOPEZ: Many years.

00:30:26.110 --> 00:30:34.280
So I, a practicing
Buddhist, I'm trying.

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:36.750
But you know what a trip it
is, that my grandmother would

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:40.590
see them around San
Fernando, and tease them.

00:30:40.590 --> 00:30:42.600
And then they were always
around me, so I said,

00:30:42.600 --> 00:30:44.850
there has to be a reason why
they're always around me,

00:30:44.850 --> 00:30:47.340
so I met Ming through that.

00:30:47.340 --> 00:30:49.119
Yes, sir.

00:30:49.119 --> 00:30:51.660
AUDIENCE: Thank you for coming
to the Pebble Beach tournament

00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:52.770
as frequently as you do.

00:30:52.770 --> 00:30:54.540
You and Bill Murray
make the tournament,

00:30:54.540 --> 00:30:57.057
so please continue
coming to that.

00:30:57.057 --> 00:30:58.140
GEORGE LOPEZ: I love golf.

00:30:58.140 --> 00:31:02.560
You know, I never would imagine
that I would be a golfer,

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:08.380
but you know, it taught me
things that a human being

00:31:08.380 --> 00:31:09.360
didn't teach me.

00:31:09.360 --> 00:31:10.620
KEVIN VLK: Well, we've got
mini putt- putt out here.

00:31:10.620 --> 00:31:12.036
GEORGE LOPEZ: Yeah,
I'll go there.

00:31:12.036 --> 00:31:14.420
AUDIENCE: So, George, I'm
not much on the links,

00:31:14.420 --> 00:31:17.359
but I happen to be a
professional mini golf player.

00:31:17.359 --> 00:31:18.150
GEORGE LOPEZ: Nice.

