GEORGE LOPEZ: I won't lose.

00:31:39.416 --> 00:31:40.535
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:41.810 --> 00:31:44.580
Now that there's a flap
in the back, tambien.

00:31:47.167 --> 00:31:48.750
KEVIN VLK: See Hector
on your way out.

00:31:48.750 --> 00:31:50.375
GEORGE LOPEZ: If it
didn't have a flap,

00:31:50.375 --> 00:31:52.626
I'm not sure I would play
you, but that had a flap.

00:31:52.626 --> 00:31:53.667
KEVIN VLK: Next question.

00:31:56.090 --> 00:31:59.520
AUDIENCE: You talk a lot about,
or you did earlier, about fear.

00:31:59.520 --> 00:32:02.460
And I'm thinking about Latino
households, especially those

00:32:02.460 --> 00:32:06.150
without a lot of resources, just
how much heartache there is.

00:32:06.150 --> 00:32:07.050
Because it's tough.

00:32:07.050 --> 00:32:08.883
It's tough for parents,
it's tough for kids,

00:32:08.883 --> 00:32:10.110
yet that humor is there.

00:32:10.110 --> 00:32:11.340
And that, like, resilience.

00:32:11.340 --> 00:32:13.840
And that, like,
even if you're never

00:32:13.840 --> 00:32:15.975
given positive
reinforcement, you

00:32:15.975 --> 00:32:19.850
know, like other families
are, people make it.

00:32:19.850 --> 00:32:23.040
And I'm wondering, I just feel
that anxiety and depression

00:32:23.040 --> 00:32:27.460
are so prevalent, and humor
is such an antidote for that.

00:32:27.460 --> 00:32:30.160
And just wondering how you
think about your ability

00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:31.460
to influence.

00:32:31.460 --> 00:32:33.580
I'm thinking about dads
out there, who are like,

00:32:33.580 --> 00:32:35.540
they're beating down
their own demons,

00:32:35.540 --> 00:32:38.902
and trying to raise kids
and not transmit that pain.

00:32:38.902 --> 00:32:39.860
What are your thoughts?

00:32:39.860 --> 00:32:45.700
GEORGE LOPEZ: You know,
that is a great question,

00:32:45.700 --> 00:32:49.740
because I didn't have a father.

00:32:49.740 --> 00:32:51.240
I never met my father.

00:32:51.240 --> 00:32:56.310
And my mother was
not well, mentally.

00:32:56.310 --> 00:33:01.620
And I took a lot
of abuse as a kid.

00:33:01.620 --> 00:33:04.950
And my grandparents
were disconnected,

00:33:04.950 --> 00:33:07.860
and never encouraging to me.

00:33:07.860 --> 00:33:10.280
Never encouraging to me.

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:15.870
And I just didn't want to become
what I had seen, or was seeing.

00:33:15.870 --> 00:33:18.750
You know, and it's very
difficult, even now,

00:33:18.750 --> 00:33:20.380
but that is definitely right.

00:33:20.380 --> 00:33:22.955
There is a responsibility
that fathers have,

00:33:22.955 --> 00:33:29.700
and family has, to at least
encourage, or talk to, or not

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:35.150
talk at, or scream at children.

00:33:35.150 --> 00:33:39.230
Because a wound,
it stays with you.

00:33:39.230 --> 00:33:42.210
And then, like something
kind, stays with you too.

00:33:42.210 --> 00:33:48.280
Because I was always the darkest
of anybody of my friends.

00:33:48.280 --> 00:33:52.820
And I always felt bad about it.

00:33:52.820 --> 00:33:54.210
Like, you know,
all Mexicans have

00:33:54.210 --> 00:33:56.940
a lemon tree in the backyard.

00:33:56.940 --> 00:33:59.850
So I used to rub
lemons on my arms,

00:33:59.850 --> 00:34:03.010
to try to lighten my skin.

00:34:03.010 --> 00:34:04.990
Didn't work.

00:34:04.990 --> 00:34:09.340
But then one of the first
complements that I ever

00:34:09.340 --> 00:34:13.679
really remember getting was,
I was at a department store,

00:34:13.679 --> 00:34:16.010
and an African American
woman said to me,

00:34:16.010 --> 00:34:19.980
you have beautiful skin.

00:34:19.980 --> 00:34:21.679
Beautiful color skin.

00:34:21.679 --> 00:34:24.370
And I never forgot it.

00:34:24.370 --> 00:34:26.940
And it meant a lot.

00:34:26.940 --> 00:34:30.170
So even little
encouraging things

00:34:30.170 --> 00:34:32.170
mean a lot to kids,
and to people.

00:34:32.170 --> 00:34:34.630
And that's what I think
we should pass on,

00:34:34.630 --> 00:34:38.820
is that critical
is too critical,

00:34:38.820 --> 00:34:39.940
and somewhere in between.

00:34:39.940 --> 00:34:43.699
Where you can't coddle
everybody, but also,

00:34:43.699 --> 00:34:47.042
you can't give them
everything, either.

00:34:47.042 --> 00:34:47.750
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:34:47.750 --> 00:34:48.420
GEORGE LOPEZ: So, thank you.

00:34:48.420 --> 00:34:49.120
Was that a good answer?

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:50.036
Because that was long.

00:34:53.554 --> 00:34:55.179
AUDIENCE: Hi, thank
you for joining us.

00:34:55.179 --> 00:34:57.695
I had a question on
Hollywood and globalization.

00:34:57.695 --> 00:34:59.820
And you were mentioning,
you know, these audiences.

00:34:59.820 --> 00:35:02.174
What do you see in
the next 20 years

00:35:02.174 --> 00:35:03.340
for entertainment, globally?

00:35:03.340 --> 00:35:05.230
GEORGE LOPEZ: Well, you know,
what I would like to see,

00:35:05.230 --> 00:35:07.510
which I think is we're
suffering a little bit from,

00:35:07.510 --> 00:35:11.500
is when movies are made, they're
made for a particular audience.

00:35:11.500 --> 00:35:15.050
And you look at movies that
are predominantly all white,

00:35:15.050 --> 00:35:16.890
or a movie that's
predominantly all black.

00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:20.770
And I think we have to start
to incorporate, instead

00:35:20.770 --> 00:35:29.920
of trends of actors, an actual
diversity of actors in movies.

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:33.544
When they cast movies, that
it looks more like real life.

00:35:33.544 --> 00:35:34.960
You know, Woody
Allen does movies,

00:35:34.960 --> 00:35:37.887
and there's never anybody
of any color in the movies.

00:35:37.887 --> 00:35:39.470
And it's a little
bit of a disservice,

00:35:39.470 --> 00:35:42.070
that you see a guy that's
such a great filmmaker,

00:35:42.070 --> 00:35:45.224
and he chooses to do a
movie like that in New York,

00:35:45.224 --> 00:35:46.640
and it doesn't
look like New York.

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:50.870
So incorporating
diversity, and I

00:35:50.870 --> 00:35:53.320
don't think there is even an
organization that makes sure

00:35:53.320 --> 00:35:55.910
that there is
diversity in movies.

00:35:55.910 --> 00:36:00.500
But the producers, and
the people that write,

00:36:00.500 --> 00:36:02.150
and the movie studios
have to be more

00:36:02.150 --> 00:36:07.880
responsible in getting more
of a mix of what looks like.

00:36:07.880 --> 00:36:12.850
You know, Asian, and what
the world looks like.

00:36:15.440 --> 00:36:16.960
Yeah, so, absolutely.

00:36:16.960 --> 00:36:19.520
And then when I did my show,
I tried to include everybody.

00:36:19.520 --> 00:36:20.670
I think that's one
of the reasons why

00:36:20.670 --> 00:36:23.044
it's so successful, is that
I tried to include everybody.

00:36:23.044 --> 00:36:24.890
And not exclude
anybody, but include.

00:36:24.890 --> 00:36:27.230
Like, you know, with my
humour, it may, at times,

00:36:27.230 --> 00:36:30.580
look like it's divisive, but
it's meant to be inclusive,

00:36:30.580 --> 00:36:32.530
to where we say, you
know, we're here too.

00:36:32.530 --> 00:36:33.450
We matter.

00:36:33.450 --> 00:36:38.270
You know the Mexican
director that won an Academy

00:36:38.270 --> 00:36:42.450
Award for "Bird Man,"
and then everybody's

00:36:42.450 --> 00:36:47.490
pissed off because he's
Mexican, and he's from Mexico.

00:36:47.490 --> 00:36:49.490
And even Sean Penn,
who-- that's cool,

00:36:49.490 --> 00:36:51.200
if they're friends,
that's all right.

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:53.640
But to say, you know, who
gave this guy his green card,

00:36:53.640 --> 00:36:54.740
as a joke?

00:36:54.740 --> 00:36:58.007
Maybe, you know, in a bar,
but not at the Oscars,

00:36:58.007 --> 00:37:00.090
because it's hard to tell
if that's a joke or not.

00:37:00.090 --> 00:37:01.810
You know, and even though
they're friends, you know,

00:37:01.810 --> 00:37:04.830
this and that, there's a place
for it, and a place not for it.

00:37:04.830 --> 00:37:06.600
But you know, Donald Trump.

00:37:06.600 --> 00:37:09.100
So you see Donald Trump
like Captain America.

00:37:09.100 --> 00:37:15.860
He says, you know, Mexico
is sending over criminals.

00:37:15.860 --> 00:37:17.220
We're not all criminals.

00:37:17.220 --> 00:37:19.770
Some are, most aren't.

00:37:19.770 --> 00:37:22.410
But then he's like, you know,
we've got to close the border,

00:37:22.410 --> 00:37:24.770
this guy wins an Academy Award.

00:37:24.770 --> 00:37:29.010
And he puts in a tweet,
Mexico, pay me back the money

00:37:29.010 --> 00:37:30.290
you owe me.

00:37:30.290 --> 00:37:32.545
So I Tweeted him back,
listen, if you ever

00:37:32.545 --> 00:37:33.920
lend money to a
Mexican, you know

00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:37.490
you don't get it all right away.

00:37:37.490 --> 00:37:40.260
You're going to
get installments.

00:37:40.260 --> 00:37:45.080
And I put
#igetpaideverytwoweeks,

00:37:45.080 --> 00:37:48.970
#ihavemydaughterthisweekend,
#illpayyounexttimeiseeyou.

00:37:52.300 --> 00:37:54.440
So, you know, there's
humor in that.

00:37:54.440 --> 00:38:00.550
But ignorance, I think,
is the enemy of us,

00:38:00.550 --> 00:38:02.420
not anybody of any
particular color.

00:38:02.420 --> 00:38:06.740
I think ignorance is
the enemy, not people.

00:38:06.740 --> 00:38:07.740
Stupid people, at least.

00:38:07.740 --> 00:38:09.198
KEVIN VLK: Well,
I read an article,

00:38:09.198 --> 00:38:10.931
and it must be true,
because I read it.

00:38:10.931 --> 00:38:13.180
But Hispanics comprise the
fastest growing demographic

00:38:13.180 --> 00:38:14.780
in the US box office.

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:16.730
So they're actually
contributing almost 20%

00:38:16.730 --> 00:38:19.040
of the US box office
revenue of all movies.

00:38:19.040 --> 00:38:21.780
And they represent only about
17.5% of the population.

00:38:21.780 --> 00:38:23.190
So it's huge.

00:38:23.190 --> 00:38:26.340
And it's interesting that
movies just aren't-- is that

00:38:26.340 --> 00:38:28.169
the politics of
Hollywood, and stuff?

00:38:28.169 --> 00:38:29.210
Do you want to change it?

00:38:29.210 --> 00:38:29.959
Can you change it?

00:38:29.959 --> 00:38:32.752
GEORGE LOPEZ: I think can.

00:38:32.752 --> 00:38:34.210
You know, I produced
"Spare Parts."

00:38:34.210 --> 00:38:36.126
You know it's harder to
find movies like that.

00:38:36.126 --> 00:38:38.540
But you keep doing
movies, and then

00:38:38.540 --> 00:38:41.229
keep-- you know, we did
"Rio," probably made

00:38:41.229 --> 00:38:42.520
a billion dollars, both movies.

00:38:42.520 --> 00:38:43.980
And the director
was from Brazil.

00:38:43.980 --> 00:38:45.820
And he had great music.

00:38:45.820 --> 00:38:48.750
I mean, great, great music.

00:38:48.750 --> 00:38:53.730
And he actually wanted
me to try to speak

00:38:53.730 --> 00:38:55.100
with a Brazilian accent.

00:38:59.540 --> 00:39:01.020
And I tried, like,
I had a coach.

00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:03.510
I'm like, oh my god,
this isn't going to work.

00:39:03.510 --> 00:39:07.680
And then, thank god
that Fox told him,

00:39:07.680 --> 00:39:11.060
listen, if we hire George Lopez,
we want that bird to sound

00:39:11.060 --> 00:39:11.920
like George Lopez.

00:39:11.920 --> 00:39:14.330
Phew.

00:39:14.330 --> 00:39:16.902
Thank god.

00:39:16.902 --> 00:39:18.360
But I've done a
lot with the voice.

00:39:18.360 --> 00:39:21.245
You know, the voice
is very recognizable.

00:39:21.245 --> 00:39:23.390
You know, a very
recognizable voice,

00:39:23.390 --> 00:39:25.945
that I didn't think, you
know, anything of it.

00:39:25.945 --> 00:39:28.070
And then sometimes I'll
call a place, and I'll say,

00:39:28.070 --> 00:39:29.445
hey, what time do
you guys close?

00:39:29.445 --> 00:39:32.210
And they're like, who is this?

00:39:32.210 --> 00:39:36.570
But in those movies, you know,
in "Beverly Hills Chihuahua,"

00:39:36.570 --> 00:39:37.742
and what other ones?

00:39:37.742 --> 00:39:38.450
KEVIN VLK: "Rio."

00:39:38.450 --> 00:39:39.400
GEORGE LOPEZ: "Rio." "Smurfs."

00:39:39.400 --> 00:39:40.040
I'm a Smurf!

00:39:40.040 --> 00:39:43.930
Like a Chicano Smurf.

00:39:43.930 --> 00:39:44.850
Grouchy.

00:39:44.850 --> 00:39:46.630
KEVIN VLK: Grouchy,
doesn't fit you.

00:39:46.630 --> 00:39:48.010
GEORGE LOPEZ: And I think
they had him like that,

00:39:48.010 --> 00:39:48.843
too, in one picture.

00:39:52.870 --> 00:39:55.370
KEVIN VLK: Do you enjoy doing
the voiceover work in a booth?

00:39:55.370 --> 00:39:56.786
GEORGE LOPEZ: You
know what, I do.

00:39:56.786 --> 00:40:03.910
I enjoy contributing, so
kids have something to watch.

00:40:03.910 --> 00:40:06.150
You know, that kids
have something to watch.

00:40:06.150 --> 00:40:13.280
It's important, because I never
thought of myself like either

00:40:13.280 --> 00:40:16.320
a leader in any way, or more
important than anybody else,

00:40:16.320 --> 00:40:18.395
but I always respect the past.

00:40:18.395 --> 00:40:21.900
You know, like I have a star
on the Hollywood Walk of Fame,

00:40:21.900 --> 00:40:26.780
and I got it the day that the
show had the hundredth episode,

00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:27.800
that day.

00:40:27.800 --> 00:40:32.100
And the guy said
to me, I think we

00:40:32.100 --> 00:40:35.520
want to put a star
into the Walk of Fame.

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:39.490
And I said, I can do it.

00:40:39.490 --> 00:40:44.040
I can't go in until
Freddie Prinze goes in.

00:40:44.040 --> 00:40:46.040
And then he said,
I think he's in.

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:47.540
And I said, I don't think so.

00:40:47.540 --> 00:40:49.780
So they checked,
and he wasn't in.

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:52.550
And I paid the money
so that Freddie Prinze

00:40:52.550 --> 00:40:54.300
could have his star.

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:55.925
And I was there, and
his son was there,

00:40:55.925 --> 00:40:57.676
and his ex-wife was
there, and his mom

00:40:57.676 --> 00:40:59.550
was on the phone from
Puerto Rico and crying.

00:41:02.665 --> 00:41:06.600
So that, the mom was, wow, man.

00:41:06.600 --> 00:41:09.165
Because, you know, everybody
kind of forgot about him,

00:41:09.165 --> 00:41:13.770
and the mom said to me,
if Freddie was alive,

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:15.345
you guys would be friends.

00:41:15.345 --> 00:41:19.485
And I was like, that's nice.

00:41:19.485 --> 00:41:20.740
I'm not crying at Google.

00:41:20.740 --> 00:41:22.552
Nobody cries at Google.

00:41:22.552 --> 00:41:24.010
KEVIN VLK: Somebody
give him a hug.

00:41:24.010 --> 00:41:25.380
GEORGE LOPEZ: I'm gonna
go somewhere, I'm gonna.

00:41:25.380 --> 00:41:26.260
AUDIENCE: Why are you crying?

00:41:26.260 --> 00:41:26.662
GEORGE LOPEZ: I know,
why are you crying?

00:41:26.662 --> 00:41:28.270
AUDIENCE: Why are you crying?

00:41:28.270 --> 00:41:29.280
GEORGE LOPEZ: All
right, now I'm over it.

00:41:29.280 --> 00:41:29.950
KEVIN VLK: It's the lights.

00:41:29.950 --> 00:41:32.130
GEORGE LOPEZ: Now I'm
over it, I'm over it.

00:41:32.130 --> 00:41:37.670
So the next one I did, that
I had to do, to honor-- thing

00:41:37.670 --> 00:41:39.690
was that Richard Pryor
had a statue in Peoria

00:41:39.690 --> 00:41:41.070
that was half done.

00:41:41.070 --> 00:41:44.260
And then I asked all those
guys to help me raise the money

00:41:44.260 --> 00:41:45.312
to get the statute done.

00:41:45.312 --> 00:41:46.770
And then we raised
the money, and I

00:41:46.770 --> 00:41:49.660
think the statue is going to
be unveiled in May, completely

00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:51.640
done, in his hometown.

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:55.040
And I think, so, I've done that
to the people that, you know,

00:41:55.040 --> 00:41:55.840
inspired me.

00:41:55.840 --> 00:41:56.528
That was nice.

00:41:56.528 --> 00:41:57.319
KEVIN VLK: Awesome.

00:41:57.319 --> 00:42:02.064
[APPLAUSE]

00:42:02.064 --> 00:42:04.022
AUDIENCE: Odelay, George,
what's going on, man?

00:42:04.022 --> 00:42:05.610
GEORGE LOPEZ: What's happening?

00:42:05.610 --> 00:42:07.151
AUDIENCE: First, I
want to say thanks

00:42:07.151 --> 00:42:09.532
for coming through, to Google.

00:42:09.532 --> 00:42:10.740
Seriously, it's been amazing.

00:42:10.740 --> 00:42:12.589
Like, if there was
like a heat map,

00:42:12.589 --> 00:42:14.130
of like, where the
[SPEAKING SPANISH]

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:18.146
at, it would be, like really
red in this area right now.

00:42:18.146 --> 00:42:19.740
[APPLAUSE]

00:42:19.740 --> 00:42:24.170
And I think it's due to
you, and your presence.

00:42:24.170 --> 00:42:26.865
Seriously, I have been a fan,
like, for the longest time,

00:42:26.865 --> 00:42:27.870
since you were in radio.

00:42:27.870 --> 00:42:29.960
And just a long time.

00:42:29.960 --> 00:42:32.690
So I wanted to say, you
know, I see you sort of as,

00:42:32.690 --> 00:42:36.910
like-- you know, the
movie, "Spare Parts,"

00:42:36.910 --> 00:42:41.410
I thought that that was like a
modern day "Stand and Deliver."

00:42:41.410 --> 00:42:43.220
Like that story was
resonating again,

00:42:43.220 --> 00:42:45.750
for like, the audiences
that were growing up now.

00:42:45.750 --> 00:42:48.255
So, you know, like, how
do I reach these kids?

00:42:48.255 --> 00:42:50.900
You know what I mean?

00:42:50.900 --> 00:42:54.270
I wanted to say, what do
you think about TV now?

00:42:54.270 --> 00:42:57.960
Like if you look, I mean, we
have "Cristela," "Blackish,"

00:42:57.960 --> 00:42:59.410
"Fresh Off the Boat."

00:42:59.410 --> 00:43:03.322
You know, TV's become
a little more colored.

00:43:03.322 --> 00:43:05.780
And I like it, but I wanted to
see what your take is on it.

00:43:05.780 --> 00:43:07.690
GEORGE LOPEZ: Those are all
ABC shows, too, by the way.

00:43:07.690 --> 00:43:08.314
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:43:08.314 --> 00:43:13.560
GEORGE LOPEZ: So ABC, I think
ABC leads the way in diversity

00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:14.520
on TV.

00:43:14.520 --> 00:43:15.390
You know, culture.

00:43:15.390 --> 00:43:21.330
You know, when I was on TV,
Damon Wayans had a show at ABC.

00:43:21.330 --> 00:43:24.640
Wanda Sykes was at Fox.

00:43:24.640 --> 00:43:28.900
Bernie Mac, god rest him, was
over there at Fox, as well.

00:43:28.900 --> 00:43:32.869
And there was much
more diversity in TV

00:43:32.869 --> 00:43:34.160
10 years ago than there is now.

00:43:34.160 --> 00:43:36.860
And that's the saddest
part, is that as we

00:43:36.860 --> 00:43:40.260
progress as a culture,
and get more intelligent,

00:43:40.260 --> 00:43:46.050
that we leave that impression
that people don't matter.

00:43:46.050 --> 00:43:48.960
They do matter.

00:43:48.960 --> 00:43:50.490
Everybody's like everybody else.

00:43:50.490 --> 00:43:51.920
You know, you're human.

00:43:51.920 --> 00:43:54.720
But if you watch TV,
and kids see that,

00:43:54.720 --> 00:43:56.690
they need to see people
that look like them.

00:43:56.690 --> 00:43:58.440
They need to people
that sound like them.

00:43:58.440 --> 00:44:03.340
And they need to see
people that make them

00:44:03.340 --> 00:44:04.820
feel good about who they are.

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:13.940
You know, I got a message from
a Chicano kid at, I think,

00:44:13.940 --> 00:44:16.240
UC Irvine, that the
professor told him

00:44:16.240 --> 00:44:20.830
that Chicano was a derogatory
term for a Mexican.

00:44:20.830 --> 00:44:23.020
And I said, no, that's not true.

00:44:23.020 --> 00:44:24.910
And he says, well
he thinks it is.

00:44:24.910 --> 00:44:30.920
I said, I'll tell you what,
I'm gonna name my next tour,

00:44:30.920 --> 00:44:34.004
and I'm gonna put Chicano in
the title for your professor.

00:44:34.004 --> 00:44:35.420
And I started
thinking, wow, what?

00:44:38.210 --> 00:44:43.700
So somebody said tall,
dark, and handsome.

00:44:43.700 --> 00:44:44.850
And I said, wait a minute.

00:44:44.850 --> 00:44:48.290
So my tour in the HBO
special, the 15,000 seat one,

00:44:48.290 --> 00:44:50.900
was called "Tall,
Dark &amp; Chicano."

00:44:50.900 --> 00:44:54.872
So I did it, and I sent
the teacher a DVD of the--

00:44:54.872 --> 00:44:56.840
[APPLAUSE]

00:44:59.895 --> 00:45:01.550
AUDIENCE: So I get
another chance?

00:45:01.550 --> 00:45:02.256
Is that it?

00:45:02.256 --> 00:45:03.260
KEVIN VLK: Yeah,
sure, you're up here.

00:45:03.260 --> 00:45:04.510
Come on, ask another question.

00:45:06.670 --> 00:45:08.810
AUDIENCE: I guess part
of it, to let you know,

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:11.480
is that I feel like
you've obviously

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:14.460
been like an innovator,
and like a person that's

00:45:14.460 --> 00:45:16.170
been able to cross
a lot of boundaries.

00:45:16.170 --> 00:45:19.330
A lot of borders within
television and entertainment

00:45:19.330 --> 00:45:20.850
and stuff.

00:45:20.850 --> 00:45:24.030
How do you see your
role developing now,

00:45:24.030 --> 00:45:29.420
as you become wiser
and more-- as a bigger

00:45:29.420 --> 00:45:32.250
figure in Hollywood, how do you
see your role of bringing up

00:45:32.250 --> 00:45:33.804
the young [SPEAKING SPANISH]?

00:45:33.804 --> 00:45:34.970
GEORGE LOPEZ: You know what?

00:45:34.970 --> 00:45:36.210
It's interesting
that you say that,

00:45:36.210 --> 00:45:37.709
because we talked
about it at lunch.

00:45:37.709 --> 00:45:42.870
I'm going to produce a
television show, "Stand-ups,"

00:45:42.870 --> 00:45:45.850
and we're going to try to
find the next stand-ups,

00:45:45.850 --> 00:45:47.500
the next generation
of stand-ups.

00:45:47.500 --> 00:45:54.000
Male, and female, and gay,
and straight, and creative.

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:57.850
However we gotta find
them, I'm gonna do a show

00:45:57.850 --> 00:45:59.670
and host it, and produce
it, and find them.

00:45:59.670 --> 00:46:04.289
And not necessarily Latino,
I'm gonna do it for everybody.

00:46:04.289 --> 00:46:05.330
Because that's important.

00:46:05.330 --> 00:46:08.180
I mean, it would be a disservice
for me to do all this,

00:46:08.180 --> 00:46:10.350
and then leave nothing.

00:46:10.350 --> 00:46:14.320
Leave no influence behind,
other than people watching me.

00:46:14.320 --> 00:46:16.155
And I don't want to
watch me no more.

00:46:16.155 --> 00:46:17.130
KEVIN VLK: Well,
it's a great time

00:46:17.130 --> 00:46:19.046
to do it, because comedy
clubs, and comedians,

00:46:19.046 --> 00:46:21.119
and stand-up is at
a peak right now.

00:46:21.119 --> 00:46:22.160
Just all these comedians.

00:46:22.160 --> 00:46:23.180
GEORGE LOPEZ: And
you know, the thing,

00:46:23.180 --> 00:46:25.471
like, Carnival Cruise Lines,
you know, they came to me,

00:46:25.471 --> 00:46:28.770
I think three years ago, and
they said, can we use your name

00:46:28.770 --> 00:46:29.770
on all the cruise ships?

00:46:29.770 --> 00:46:33.170
So all the cruise
ships have my name

00:46:33.170 --> 00:46:34.530
and my picture on the stage.

00:46:34.530 --> 00:46:41.740
So that was a big thing for me,
that kind of, like the brand

00:46:41.740 --> 00:46:44.330
would cross over into
something like Carnival.

00:46:44.330 --> 00:46:45.865
George Lopez, you know, nice.

00:46:45.865 --> 00:46:47.740
KEVIN VLK: That's
interesting, because I also

00:46:47.740 --> 00:46:50.250
read that you turned down
a role in the 1995 movie,

00:46:50.250 --> 00:46:52.790
"Desperado," with
Antonio Banderas.

00:46:52.790 --> 00:46:56.371
You didn't like how it promoted
negative images of Latinos.

00:46:56.371 --> 00:46:58.620
So do you do that a lot,
where you're just like, no, I

00:46:58.620 --> 00:47:00.440
can't be involved with this.

00:47:00.440 --> 00:47:01.384
It's not my brand.

00:47:01.384 --> 00:47:02.800
GEORGE LOPEZ: You
know what, I do.

00:47:02.800 --> 00:47:07.030
Because for me,
particularly, I can't do it.

00:47:07.030 --> 00:47:11.410
So when that movie-- it's
funny, because you know,

00:47:11.410 --> 00:47:15.760
you always get your integrity
questioned, you know.

00:47:15.760 --> 00:47:17.650
Like, I remember, I
read for the movie.

00:47:17.650 --> 00:47:19.490
Salma Hayek's in it.

00:47:19.490 --> 00:47:21.450
Antonio Banderas is in it.

00:47:21.450 --> 00:47:23.090
Robert Rodriguez
is directing it.

00:47:23.090 --> 00:47:24.720
So they called me,
and they said, hey,

00:47:24.720 --> 00:47:28.510
they're offering you
a part in "Desperado."

00:47:28.510 --> 00:47:33.780
And I said, yeah, what part?

00:47:33.780 --> 00:47:36.610
And they said, a drug runner.

00:47:36.610 --> 00:47:39.826
And then I literally
said, how much drugs

